'''Shichijūtō''' (七重塔) is one form of {{ill|Buddhist Pagoda|de|Pagode|ja|仏塔}}. It refers to the tower‐type Buddhist pagodas that feature seven roofs. In Japan, no large wooden seven‐tiered pagoda built until the early modern period still exists.

==Overview==
{{Image:Sagami Provincial Temple.jpg|200px|right|thumb|In Kanagawa Prefecture, the seven‐tiered pagoda of the Sagami Kokubunji was reconstructed within {{ill|Ebina Central Park|de|Ebina-Zentralpark|ja|海老名中央公園}}}}

For the meaning and significance of Buddhist pagodas, see the article on {{ill|Five-tiered Pagoda|de|Fünfstöckige Pagode|ja|五重塔}}.

In Japan, when {{ill|Emperor Shōmu|de|Kaiser Shōmu|ja|聖武天皇}} issued an {{ill|Imperial Decree|de|Kaiserlicher Erlass|ja|勅命}} to establish {{ill|Kokubunji|de|Kokubunji|ja|国分寺}} throughout the country, the construction of seven‐tiered pagodas advanced alongside temple building. Consequently, at the remains of various Kokubunji—such as {{ill|Musashi Kokubunji|de|Musashi Kokubunji|ja|武蔵国分寺跡|lt=Musashi Kokubunji|lt_ja=武蔵国分寺|lt_de=Musashi Kokubunji}}, {{ill|Awa Kokubunji|de|Awa Kokubunji|ja|阿波国分寺}}, and {{ill|Sanuki Kokubunji|de|Sanuki Kokubunji|ja|讃岐国分寺}}—some of the temple ruins include the base platform of a seven‐tiered pagoda ({{ill|Pagoda Base|de|Pagodenbasis|ja|基壇}}). At {{ill|Tōdai-ji|de|Tōdai-ji|ja|東大寺}}, two seven‐tiered pagodas (one in the east and one in the west) were constructed. During the {{ill|Heian Period|de|Heian-Zeit|ja|平安時代}}, a seven‐tiered pagoda was built at Yūgiji in ({{ill|Osaka Prefecture|de|Osaka|ja|大阪府}} – {{ill|Yao|de|Yao|ja|八尾市}}) under the auspices of {{ill|Dōkyō|de|Dōkyō|ja|道鏡}}. In the {{ill|Kamakura Period|de|Kamakura-Zeit|ja|鎌倉時代}}, the east pagoda of {{ill|Tōdai-ji|de|Tōdai-ji|ja|東大寺}} was rebuilt, and in the {{ill|Muromachi Period|de|Muromachi-Zeit|ja|室町時代}}, under the patronage of {{ill|Ashikaga Yoshimitsu|de|Ashikaga Yoshimitsu|ja|足利義満}}, a seven‐tiered pagoda (with a height of 36 {{ill|shaku|de|Shaku|ja|丈}}, approximately 109 m) was built at {{ill|Sōkoku-ji|de|Sōkoku-ji|ja|相国寺}} in {{ill|Kyoto|de|Kyoto|ja|京都市}}. Additionally, near {{ill|Kinkaku-ji|de|Kinkaku-ji|ja|金閣寺}}, a pagoda known as the Kitayama Great Pagoda was constructed; however, all these structures were subsequently destroyed by {{ill|Lightning Strike|de|Blitzschlag|ja|落雷}} or warfare. (In fact, the Kitayama Great Pagoda near Kinkaku-ji was a reconstruction—relocated from the destroyed seven‐tiered pagoda of Sōkoku-ji, which had been razed by order of Yoshimitsu. After its subsequent destruction near Kinkaku-ji following Yoshimitsu’s death, a seven‐tiered pagoda was rebuilt at the original Sōkoku-ji site at the behest of {{ill|Ashikaga Yoshimochi|de|Ashikaga Yoshimochi|ja|足利義持}}, meaning that both structures can be regarded as the same pagoda.)

