[[ja:七重塔]]
[[de:Seven-tiered Pagoda]]

'''Shichijūtō''' (七重塔) is one form of [[:en:Stupa|Buddhist Pagoda]]. It refers to the tower‐type Buddhist pagodas that feature seven roofs. In Japan, no large wooden seven‐tiered pagoda built until the early modern period still exists.

==Overview==
[[Image:Sagami Provincial Temple.jpg|200px|right|thumb|In Kanagawa Prefecture, the seven‐tiered pagoda of the Sagami Kokubunji was reconstructed within {{ill|Ebina Central Park|de|Ebina-Zentralpark|ja|海老名中央公園|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ebina Central Park|qq=}}]]

For the meaning and significance of Buddhist pagodas, see the article on {{ill|Five-tiered Pagoda|de|Fünfstöckige Pagode|ja|五重塔|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Five-tiered Pagoda|qq=}}.

In Japan, when [[:en:Emperor Shōmu|Emperor Shōmu]] issued an {{ill|Imperial Decree|de|Kaiserlicher Erlass|ja|勅命|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Imperial Decree|qq=}} to establish [[:en:Provincial temple|Kokubunji]] throughout the country, the construction of seven‐tiered pagodas advanced alongside temple building. Consequently, at the remains of various Kokubunji—such as {{ill|Musashi Kokubunji|de|Musashi Kokubunji|ja|武蔵国分寺跡|lt=Musashi Kokubunji|lt_ja=武蔵国分寺|lt_de=Musashi Kokubunji|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Musashi Kokubunji|qq=}}, {{ill|Awa Kokubunji|de|Awa Kokubunji|ja|阿波国分寺|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Awa Kokubunji|qq=}}, and [[:en:Sanuki Kokubun-ji|Sanuki Kokubunji]]—some of the temple ruins include the base platform of a seven‐tiered pagoda ({{ill|Pagoda Base|de|Pagodenbasis|ja|基壇|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Pagoda Base|qq=}}). At [[:en:Tōdai-ji|Tōdai-ji]], two seven‐tiered pagodas (one in the east and one in the west) were constructed. During the [[:en:Heian period|Heian Period]], a seven‐tiered pagoda was built at Yūgiji in ([[:en:Osaka Prefecture|Osaka Prefecture]] – [[:en:Yao, Osaka|Yao]]) under the auspices of [[:en:Dōkyō|Dōkyō]]. In the [[:en:Kamakura period|Kamakura Period]], the east pagoda of [[:en:Tōdai-ji|Tōdai-ji]] was rebuilt, and in the [[:en:Muromachi period|Muromachi Period]], under the patronage of [[:en:Ashikaga Yoshimitsu|Ashikaga Yoshimitsu]], a seven‐tiered pagoda (with a height of 36 {{ill|shaku|de|Shaku|ja|丈|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/shaku|qq=}}, approximately 109 m) was built at [[:en:Shōkoku-ji|Sōkoku-ji]] in [[:en:Kyoto|Kyoto]]. Additionally, near {{ill|Kinkaku-ji|de|Kinkaku-ji|ja|金閣寺|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kinkaku-ji|qq=}}, a pagoda known as the Kitayama Great Pagoda was constructed; however, all these structures were subsequently destroyed by [[:en:Lightning strike|Lightning Strike]] or warfare. (In fact, the Kitayama Great Pagoda near Kinkaku-ji was a reconstruction—relocated from the destroyed seven‐tiered pagoda of Sōkoku-ji, which had been razed by order of Yoshimitsu. After its subsequent destruction near Kinkaku-ji following Yoshimitsu’s death, a seven‐tiered pagoda was rebuilt at the original Sōkoku-ji site at the behest of [[:en:Ashikaga Yoshimochi|Ashikaga Yoshimochi]], meaning that both structures can be regarded as the same pagoda.)

